<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <meta name="description" content="Sensory Explorer - Complete Development Roadmap with Full Specifications">
    <title>Sensory Explorer - Development Updates & Specifications</title>
    <style>
        * { margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box; }
        body {
            font-family: 'Menlo', 'Monaco', monospace;
            background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0a0a1e 0%, #1a0a3e 50%, #0a0a1e 100%);
            color: #e0e0e0;
            line-height: 1.6;
        }
        .container { max-width: 1200px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 40px 20px; }
        h1 { font-size: 2.5rem; background: linear-gradient(135deg, #00d9ff, #667eea); -webkit-background-clip: text; -webkit-text-fill-color: transparent; background-clip: text; margin-bottom: 10px; }
        .subtitle { color: #999; font-size: 1.1rem; margin-bottom: 40px; }
        h2 { color: #00d9ff; font-size: 1.8rem; margin-top: 50px; margin-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0,217,255,0.3); padding-bottom: 10px; }
        h3 { color: #667eea; font-size: 1.3rem; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 15px; }
        .section { background: rgba(15, 15, 40, 0.8); border: 1px solid rgba(0, 217, 255, 0.2); border-radius: 12px; padding: 30px; margin-bottom: 30px; }
        .subsection { background: rgba(20, 20, 50, 0.8); border-left: 3px solid rgba(102, 126, 234, 0.5); padding: 20px; margin: 20px 0; border-radius: 6px; }
        .card-block { background: rgba(25, 25, 60, 0.7); border: 1px solid rgba(0, 217, 255, 0.15); padding: 20px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 8px; }
        .card-view { background: rgba(20, 20, 50, 0.9); padding: 15px; border-radius: 6px; margin-bottom: 10px; }
        .card-modal { background: rgba(15, 15, 40, 0.9); padding: 15px; border-left: 3px solid #667eea; border-radius: 6px; margin-top: 10px; }
        .headline { color: #00d9ff; font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: bold; margin-bottom: 8px; }
        .subtext { color: #999; font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 10px; }
        .modal-title { color: #667eea; font-size: 1rem; font-weight: bold; margin-bottom: 10px; margin-top: 10px; }
        .modal-body { color: #ddd; font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.7; }
        .cta-button { display: inline-block; padding: 8px 16px; background: rgba(0, 217, 255, 0.2); color: #00d9ff; border: 1px solid #00d9ff; border-radius: 4px; margin: 5px 5px 5px 0; cursor: pointer; font-size: 0.85rem; }
        .cta-link { color: #00d9ff; text-decoration: none; cursor: pointer; font-size: 0.9rem; }
        .cta-link:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
        ul { list-style: none; padding-left: 20px; }
        li { padding: 8px 0; }
        li::before { content: '→ '; color: #00d9ff; font-weight: bold; }
        .status { display: inline-block; padding: 4px 12px; border-radius: 4px; font-size: 0.85rem; margin-left: 10px; font-weight: bold; }
        .done { background: rgba(40, 167, 69, 0.3); color: #28a745; }
        .inprogress { background: rgba(102, 126, 234, 0.3); color: #667eea; }
        .planned { background: rgba(233, 30, 99, 0.3); color: #e91e63; }
        .critical { background: rgba(220, 20, 60, 0.3); color: #ff4444; }
        code { background: rgba(0,0,0,0.4); padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 3px; font-family: 'Courier New', monospace; color: #00d9ff; }
        pre { background: rgba(0,0,0,0.6); padding: 15px; border-radius: 6px; overflow-x: auto; margin: 15px 0; border-left: 3px solid #667eea; }
        table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 20px 0; }
        th, td { padding: 12px; text-align: left; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(0, 217, 255, 0.2); }
        th { background: rgba(102, 126, 234, 0.2); color: #00d9ff; }
        .flow-diagram { background: rgba(20, 20, 50, 0.5); padding: 20px; border-radius: 6px; margin: 20px 0; font-family: monospace; white-space: pre-wrap; color: #00d9ff; }
        a { color: #00d9ff; text-decoration: none; }
        a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>🚀 Sensory Explorer</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">Complete Development Roadmap & Full Specifications</p>

        <!-- ONBOARDING REDESIGN -->
        <h2>📱 Onboarding Redesign (Card + Modal Pattern)</h2>
        
        <div class="section">
            <h3>Overview</h3>
            <p style="margin-bottom: 15px;">
                <strong>9-Card Journey:</strong> Each card shows a clean headline + image + subtext. Tap [Learn More ℹ️] for full explanation in modal. Tap [Next →] to skip and proceed.
            </p>
            <p style="margin-bottom: 15px;">
                <strong>Why This Pattern?</strong> Cards stay scannable & uncluttered. Full educational copy available for parents who want depth. Respects different learning styles.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Card Count:</strong> 9 cards total (empathy → education → action → personalization)
            </p>
        </div>

        <h3>Card Journey Flow</h3>
        <div class="flow-diagram">Card 1: Problem (Empathy)
     ↓
Card 2: Science (SOS Method)
     ↓
Card 3: Bridge Foods Strategy
     ↓
Card 4: Outcomes (Success)
     ↓
Card 5: Explorer Selection
     ↓
Card 6-7: Safe Foods Collection
     ↓
Card 8: Sensory Profile Summary
     ↓
Card 9: Goal Food + First Action
        </div>

        <!-- CARD 1 -->
        <div class="subsection">
            <h3>CARD 1: Problem Statement (Empathy Hook)</h3>
            
            <div class="card-block">
                <div class="card-view">
                    <div class="headline">"Your Child Isn't Picky. They're Sensory-Sensitive."</div>
                    <div class="subtext">It's neurological. It's real. And there's a science-backed way to help.</div>
                    <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
                        <span class="cta-link">ℹ️ Learn More</span> | <span class="cta-button">Next →</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="card-modal">
                    <div class="modal-title">Why This Matters</div>
                    <div class="modal-body">
You know your child. You know mealtimes are stressful. You know they eat from a tiny list of foods.

And you know it's not stubbornness. It's not behavior. It's sensory.

Their nervous system processes textures, tastes, and temperatures differently. What feels smooth to you might feel wrong to them. What smells good might feel overwhelming.

The good news? Sensory sensitivity is rewirable. With the right approach and patience, kids can expand their food world naturally—without pressure, without battles.

You're not alone. 1 in 3 children experience selective eating tied to sensory sensitivity.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <p><strong>Visual:</strong> Child at table looking at plate with slight anxiety, parent behind looking supportive. Dark starfield background, warm lighting, cyan borders.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- CARD 2 -->
        <div class="subsection">
            <h3>CARD 2: The Science (SOS Approach)</h3>
            
            <div class="card-block">
                <div class="card-view">
                    <div class="headline">"Gentle Progress, Not Forced Eating"</div>
                    <div style="color: #d4af37; font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 8px;">The SOS Approach – 30+ Years of Research</div>
                    <div class="subtext">5 sensory phases. No pressure. No bribes.</div>
                    <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
                        <span class="cta-link">ℹ️ Learn More</span> | <span class="cta-button">Next →</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="card-modal">
                    <div class="modal-title">What is the SOS Approach?</div>
                    <div class="modal-body">
We use the Sequential Oral Sensory (SOS) Approach—the same method occupational therapists and speech therapists have used for 30+ years.

Here's how it works: Instead of pressure or bribes, we work WITH your child's nervous system.

👁️ LOOK — Getting used to seeing the food
🙌 TOUCH — Exploring textures with their hands
👃 SMELL — Experiencing the aroma
👅 LICK — Trying tiny tastes
😋 TASTE — Eating and enjoying

Each phase takes 3-10 days. No rushing. Your child's nervous system needs time to process each new sensation. That's not slow—that's smart.

Research shows children using the SOS Approach see measurable improvements in food acceptance within weeks to months—not years of battles.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <p><strong>Visual:</strong> 5 sensory icons (eye, hand, nose, tongue, mouth) arranged vertically with glowing cyan/gold effects. Small food items nearby. Space-themed background.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- CARD 3 -->
        <div class="subsection">
            <h3>CARD 3: Bridge Foods (The Secret)</h3>
            
            <div class="card-block">
                <div class="card-view">
                    <div class="headline">"Bridge Foods: The Secret Weapon"</div>
                    <div class="subtext">Meet them where they are. Expand from there.</div>
                    <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
                        <span class="cta-link">ℹ️ Learn More</span> | <span class="cta-button">Next →</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="card-modal">
                    <div class="modal-title">How Bridge Foods Work</div>
                    <div class="modal-body">
Here's where the magic happens.

Your child has foods they already like and eat comfortably. Chicken nuggets. Crackers. Pasta. Whatever they trust.

A "bridge food" shares the same sensory qualities as those safe foods—but introduces something slightly new.

Real Example:
→ If they like crunchy, salty crackers
→ Try crunchy, salty pretzels (similar texture, new taste)
→ Then gradually explore other crunchy snacks

It's not random. It's strategic. You're meeting them where they are, then slowly expanding from there.

This App Helps By:
Analyzing your child's favorite foods, identifying what they like (textures, flavors, temperatures), and suggesting bridge foods they're most likely to accept.

This is how selective eaters become adventurous eaters. One bridge at a time.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <p><strong>Visual:</strong> Safe food → Bridge food → New food (progression arrows). Sensory traits labeled (crunchy, warm, salty). Example: Crackers → Pretzels → Breadsticks.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- CARD 4 -->
        <div class="subsection">
            <h3>CARD 4: Outcomes (The Promise)</h3>
            
            <div class="card-block">
                <div class="card-view">
                    <div class="headline">"Track Every Victory (Big & Small)"</div>
                    <div class="subtext">Celebrate progress your child can see.</div>
                    <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
                        <span class="cta-link">ℹ️ Learn More</span> | <span class="cta-button">Next →</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="card-modal">
                    <div class="modal-title">What You'll Get</div>
                    <div class="modal-body">
Success looks like your child getting braver, one food at a time. And you'll see it happening.

FOR YOU (Parent):
📊 Dashboard showing food variety expanding (textures, colors, flavors)
📈 Trend reports: What's working? What's next?
📤 Export progress for therapists or pediatricians
📅 Timeline showing how far they've come

FOR YOUR CHILD:
🎮 Galaxy to explore (8 planets, 5 sensory phases each)
🧑‍🚀 Their own explorer character they level up
🔥 Daily streaks + badges + rewards
✨ Proof they're getting braver

THE REAL OUTCOME:
After weeks of consistent logging, you'll see the pattern. Your child is trying new things. Getting more confident. Growing independent around food.

Not because you forced it. Because they felt safe to explore.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <p><strong>Visual:</strong> Split-screen: Left = parent dashboard (charts, analytics), Right = kid explorer (galaxy, badges, fire streaks). Full brand colors.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- CARD 5 -->
        <div class="subsection">
            <h3>CARD 5: Explorer Selection</h3>
            
            <div class="card-block">
                <div class="card-view">
                    <div class="headline">"Pick Your Explorer"</div>
                    <div class="subtext">You'll unlock cosmetics together.</div>
                    <p style="margin-top: 15px; color: #999; font-size: 0.85rem;">Shows 4 explorer buttons: Nova (Cyan), Cosmo (Purple), Star (Gold), Orbit (Pink)</p>
                    <p style="color: #999; font-size: 0.85rem; margin-top: 10px;">[Name Your Explorer] text input</p>
                    <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
                        <span class="cta-button">Continue →</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <p><strong>NO MODAL</strong> — Direct selection on card. Each explorer shows name + title + bio.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- CARD 6-7 -->
        <div class="subsection">
            <h3>CARD 6-7: Safe Foods Collection</h3>
            
            <div class="card-block">
                <div class="card-view">
                    <div class="headline">"What Foods Does [Child] Already Like?"</div>
                    <div class="subtext">Select as many as you'd like. More = better recommendations.</div>
                    <p style="margin-top: 15px; color: #999; font-size: 0.85rem;">Scrollable grid of ~40 food options with icons + names. Checkboxes to select.</p>
                    <p style="color: #999; font-size: 0.85rem; margin-top: 10px;">Counter: "[X] selected"</p>
                    <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
                        <span class="cta-button">Skip</span> <span class="cta-button">Continue →</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <p><strong>KEY PRINCIPLE:</strong> Do NOT reduce upfront foods. MORE foods = MORE personalization. Let parents add 3-5 initial, then encourage adding more for better AI recommendations.</p>
            <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>NO MODAL</strong> — Direct multi-select interface.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- CARD 8 -->
        <div class="subsection">
            <h3>CARD 8: Sensory Profile Summary</h3>
            
            <div class="card-block">
                <div class="card-view">
                    <div class="headline">"Here's What We Learned"</div>
                    <div class="subtext">Your personalized sensory summary</div>
                    <p style="margin-top: 15px; color: #ddd; font-size: 0.9rem;">
                        ✓ Safe Foods: 6 items<br/>
                        ✓ Most Common Texture: Crunchy<br/>
                        ✓ Flavor Preference: Bland/Salty<br/>
                        ✓ Temperature: Warm<br/>
                        ✓ Color Variety: Yellow, Brown, White (expand next!)
                    </p>
                    <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
                        <span class="cta-button">Continue →</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <p><strong>NO MODAL</strong> — Summary display only.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- CARD 9 -->
        <div class="subsection">
            <h3>CARD 9: Goal Food + First Action</h3>
            
            <div class="card-block">
                <div class="card-view">
                    <div class="headline">"What's Your Long-Term Goal?"</div>
                    <div class="subtext">One food you'd love them to eat someday?</div>
                    <p style="margin-top: 15px; color: #999; font-size: 0.85rem;">[Input field]: "e.g., Pizza"</p>
                    <p style="color: #999; font-size: 0.85rem; margin-top: 10px;">(Optional: Texture/Flavor/Temperature selectors)</p>
                    <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
                        <span class="cta-button">Log First Food →</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <p><strong>9B: Log First Food</strong></p>
            <div class="card-block">
                <div class="card-view">
                    <div class="headline">"Ready? Let's Start"</div>
                    <div class="subtext">Log something from today.</div>
                    <p style="margin-top: 15px; color: #999; font-size: 0.85rem;">[Input: "What food?"]<br/>[Dropdown: "What sensory phase?"] (LOOK, TOUCH, SMELL, LICK, TASTE)</p>
                    <div style="margin-top: 10px;">
                        <span class="cta-button">Log Food →</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>NO MODALS</strong> — Direct input & action.</p>
        </div>

